1.name: Jaylen Summers
1.about: A headliner in this class, he stands 6’5” with a 6’11” wingspan and elite burst. He scored 65% at the rim in halfcourt play, a rare mark for a freshman guard. His athleticism, rim pressure, and two-way upside scream franchise cornerstone.

2.name: Trey James
2.about: A smooth creator thriving in isolation and pick-and-rolls, he ranked in the 90th percentile as a PnR scorer, using crafty hesitation moves to carve out space. His blend of handle, pace, and shot-making gives him serious lead-guard upside.

3.name: Nicola Mancini
3.about: Excelling in the mid-range, he drills pull-ups at a 47% clip and ranks in the 88th percentile in pick-and-roll scoring. At 6’6” with length, he doubles as a disruptive perimeter defender. His balance of two-way impact makes him a unique backcourt prospect.

4.name: Adam Riley
4.about: Towering over the rim, he uses a 7’5 wingspan to rank top-5 among freshmen in block rate. Opponents managed just 40% at the rim when he was the primary contest. His defensive anchor potential makes him a high-upside big despite raw offensive polish.

5.name: Saúl Segura
5.about: A long wing thriving in the mid-range, he hit 46% on pull-up twos and posted 1.08 points per possession on dribble jumpers, showing polish beyond his years. With a 7’0 wingspan, his scoring craft and size intrigue scouts.

6.name: Taji Anikulapo-Kuti
6.about: One of the most disruptive wings in the class, his 7’3” wingspan fuels a 3.2 steal rate while holding opponents to just 0.71 PPP in isolation. At 19, his physicality, motor, and defensive instincts make him a prototype modern stopper.

7.name: Sincere Johnston
7.about: Thriving in isolation, he uses strength and craft to create mismatches at the wing-forward spot. He scored 0.96 points per possession on self-created looks and drew fouls at a high clip. His blend of shot creation and toughness powers his upside.

8.name: Joshua Boston
8.about: An athletic wing who puts constant pressure on the rim, converting 64% in transition and 61% at the basket in the halfcourt. At 19, his blend of size, bounce, and slashing makes him a dangerous scorer.

9.name: Ismaël Aït Salah
9.about: A versatile forward impacting the game defensively, he averaged 2.7 blocks per 40 while holding opponents to 42% inside the arc. Offensively, he thrives as a straight-line slasher but remains raw as a shooter. At 18, his upside is clear.

10.name: Riley Jamison
10.about: A shifty lead guard excelling in pick-and-roll play, posting 1.04 points per possession as a PnR ball-handler, flashing deep shooting range and creative passing. At 20, his size limits him defensively, but his playmaking and shot-making pop.

11.name: Isaiah Bailey
11.about: Bailey is a smooth iso scorer who thrives in pick-and-rolls and isolation situations. At 6’6” with a 6’9” wingspan, he averaged 0.98 points per possession on self-created looks while keeping defenders off balance. His scoring craft and versatility make him a dangerous wing prospect.

12.name: Terrence James
12.about: James is a 3-and-D wing who stretches the floor and takes pride in his perimeter defense. At 6’7” with a 6’10” wingspan, he knocked down 39% of his threes while limiting opposing guards and wings. His defensive instincts and spacing make him a valuable two-way contributor.

13.name: Bernard Johnson
13.about: Johnson is a stretch big who thrives in the post and on the perimeter. At 6’9” with a 6’11” wingspan, he averaged 1.02 points per possession on post-ups while hitting 36% of his threes. His scoring versatility makes him a dangerous two-way forward.

14.name: Chancellor Harris
14.about: Harris is a versatile guard with size and scoring ability. At 6’8”, he converts 63% at the rim and shows a developing jump shot that keeps defenders honest. His blend of finishing, playmaking, and length makes him a rare two-way prospect.

15.name: Jaylen Simmons
15.about: Simmons is a pesky defensive guard with range on his shot. At 6’1”, he averages 2.1 steals per 40 minutes and converts 38% from deep. His anticipation, court awareness, and ability to shoot from distance make him a high-upside backcourt disruptor.

16.name: Darius Hall
16.about: Hall’s presence in the paint is intimidating, altering shots with his 6’11” wingspan and averaging 2.6 blocks per 40 minutes. At 18, his length, timing, and finishing ability make him a top interior prospect.

17.name: Mark Bolton
17.about: Known for his craft in the mid-paint, Bolton creates space and finishes over bigger defenders. At 6’10” with a 7’0” wingspan, he averaged 1.01 points per possession on post-ups, showing soft touch around the rim.

18.name: Terrance Edwards
18.about: Stretching the floor and defending multiple positions, Edwards converts 41% of his threes. At 6’8” with a 6’11” wingspan, his shooting touch and defensive IQ make him a high-upside two-way small forward.

19.name: Kason Smith
19.about: Operating as a table-setting guard, Smith thrives in pick-and-rolls and off-ball action. At 6’3” with a 6’5” wingspan, he averaged 0.97 points per possession while creating open looks for teammates.

20.name: Jack Rice
20.about: Exceling in isolation and mid-range pull-ups, Rice uses crafty footwork to create space. At 6’7” with a 6’8” wingspan, he averaged 1.01 points per possession, making him a dangerous offensive wing.

21.name: Aviel Elbaz
21.about: With crafty finishing and pick-and-roll savvy, Elbaz creates scoring opportunities for himself and teammates. At 6’5” with a 6’7” wingspan, he averaged 1.02 points per possession in controlled sets.

22.name: Dave Mosley
22.about: Known as a post bully, Mosley dominates the paint with strength and physicality. At 6’8” with a 7’0” wingspan, he averaged 1.05 points per possession while cleaning the glass, making him a high-upside interior presence.

23.name: Semaj Jenkins
23.about: Disrupting passing lanes and creating turnovers, Jenkins makes life difficult for opposing wings. At 6’4” with a 6’11” wingspan, he averaged 2.1 steals per 40 minutes. His length and motor make him a defensive standout.

24.name: Xavion Booker
24.about: Excelling in mid-range scoring, Booker thrives in isolation and pick-and-roll situations. At 6’3” with a 6’5” wingspan, he converted 48% of his pull-up jumpers, using subtle footwork and deception.

25.name: Jadyn Mora
25.about: A dangerous backcourt threat, Mora shines in one-on-one situations. At 6’1” with a 6’3” wingspan, he averaged 1.00 points per possession while using hesitation moves and change-of-pace finishes.

26.name: Kavon Williams
26.about: Williams excels in creating offense off the dribble and in transition. At 6’4” with a 6’11” wingspan, he uses crafty footwork and strong finishing to get to the rim and create opportunities for teammates, while also contributing defensively with his length and activity.

27.name: Cam Lee
27.about: Lee is a mid-range specialist who creates space with clever footwork and a quick release. At 6’0” with a 6’0” wingspan, he can efficiently score off the dribble or in catch-and-shoot situations while using his instincts and vision to create for teammates.

28.name: Dustin Anderson
28.about: Anderson attacks the rim with fluidity and confidence. At 6’6” with a 6’9” wingspan, he averaged 0.98 points per possession on isolation and in transition, using size, finishing ability, and craft to create consistent scoring opportunities while contributing on defense.

29.name: Iago Barcellos
29.about: Barcellos stretches the floor while protecting the rim. At 6’10” with a 7’2” wingspan, he averaged 2.2 blocks per 40 minutes while knocking down 36% of his threes. His length, defensive timing, and shooting touch make him a versatile frontcourt contributor.

30.name: Mathys Moreau
30.about: Moreau is a stretch big who can finish inside and hit shots from deep. At 6’9” with a 6’11” wingspan, he averaged 1.02 points per possession in the post while knocking down 35% of his threes. His combination of shooting and size makes him a versatile frontcourt option.

31.name: Mahlik Joseph
31.about: Joseph excels at navigating defenses and creating opportunities for teammates while contributing on the defensive end. At 6’3” with a 6’7” wingspan, he uses strength and craft to finish at the rim and disrupt opposing guards, making him a two-way backcourt asset.

32.name: Niklas Helm
32.about: Helm is a versatile big who excels at finishing around the rim and protecting the paint. At 6’10” with a 6’11” wingspan, he averages 1.02 points per possession on putbacks and contributes defensively with timely blocks and smart rotations. His athleticism and length make him a two-way frontcourt piece.

33.name: Andrew Bolden Jr.
33.about: Bolden disrupts passing lanes and contests shots with length. At 6’6” with a 6’11” wingspan, he averaged 1.9 steals per 40 minutes, making life difficult for opposing wings. His motor and physicality give him high two-way value.

34.name: Kristiāns Lapiņš
34.about: Lapiņš is a tall interior scorer who protects the rim effectively. At 6’11” with a 7’3” wingspan, he averaged 1.01 points per possession in post-ups while contesting shots at the rim. His size, timing, and finishing ability make him a high-upside big man.

35.name: Jabari Henry
35.about: Henry attacks the rim with strength and finishing ability. At 6’6” with a 6’9” wingspan, he averaged 1.04 points per possession on putbacks and close-range attempts, using his size and craft to score efficiently while also contributing on the boards.

36.name: Justinas Jakčinskas
36.about: Using his 7’3” wingspan, Jakčinskas dominates around the rim and protects the paint. At 6’11”, he averaged 2.3 blocks per 40 minutes while finishing efficiently on putbacks. His length, timing, and defensive instincts make him a high-upside interior presence.

37.name: Nicholas Falk
37.about: Known for his floor-spacing, Falk consistently knocks down catch-and-shoot threes. At 6’6” with a 6’4” wingspan, he averaged 39% from deep while using footwork and timing to create open looks. His shooting and basketball IQ make him a reliable offensive weapon.

38.name: Luke Causey
38.about: Stretching the floor with smooth shooting, Causey also finishes efficiently in the post. At 7’0” with a 7’0” wingspan, he averaged 1.03 points per possession on post-ups while hitting 35% of his threes. His combination of size, skill, and shooting touch gives him versatility on both ends.

39.name: Cody Meadows
39.about: Combining length and shooting, Meadows stretches defenses and finishes around the rim. At 6’7” with a 6’10” wingspan, he converted 38% of his threes while using athleticism and craft to score efficiently in transition and halfcourt sets.

40.name: Mark Smiley
40.about: Operating effectively in isolation, Smiley thrives in mid-range and pull-up situations. At 6’5” with a 6’7” wingspan, he averaged 1.03 points per possession while using crafty footwork and timing to create separation. His scoring instincts and size make him a dangerous offensive wing.

41.name: Miles Gibson
41.about: Dominating the paint, Gibson uses strength and finishing ability to control post-ups. At 6’8” with a 7’2” wingspan, he averaged 1.00 points per possession while cleaning the glass. His size and power make him a reliable interior scoring option.

42.name: Davonte Huntley
42.about: A polished post scorer, Huntley excels with footwork and finishing around the rim. At 6’8” with a 6’11” wingspan, he averaged 1.01 points per possession on post-ups while cleaning the glass. His size, craft, and post moves make him a high-upside interior contributor.

43.name: Alex Humphrey
43.about: Stretching the floor with reliable perimeter shooting, Humphrey converts threes efficiently while creating space with craft and footwork. At 6’7” with a 6’8” wingspan, his size and shooting touch make him a consistent offensive contributor.

44.name: Alex Mahon
44.about: Thriving off the dribble and in catch-and-shoot situations, Mahon uses clever footwork and timing to create scoring opportunities. At 6’5” with a 6’6” wingspan, he averaged 0.97 points per possession while stretching defenses effectively.

45.name: Samy Delaunay
45.about: Attacking the rim with explosiveness, Delaunay uses athleticism and craft to finish efficiently in transition and isolation. At 6’5” with a 6’7” wingspan, he also creates opportunities for teammates while contributing defensively with length and effort.

46.name: Kevin Tyson
46.about: Tyson uses his athleticism and length to attack the rim effectively. At 6’7” with a 6’11” wingspan, he converted 62% of his attempts at the rim and averaged 1.8 assists per 40 minutes, creating scoring opportunities while pressuring defenses.

47.name: Jake Smith
47.about: Controlling the glass, Smith scores efficiently around the rim. At 6’11” with a 7’0” wingspan, he grabbed 12.3 rebounds per 40 minutes and converted 61% of his shots in the paint, providing a reliable interior presence.

48.name: Tristian Roach
48.about: Roach uses his strength and length to finish inside and create mismatches. At 6’5” with a 7’0” wingspan, he converted 58% of his rim attempts and averaged 1.5 steals per 40 minutes, impacting both ends of the floor.

49.name: Aaron Carrillo
49.about: Carrillo attacks the rim with authority and finishes through contact. At 6’8” with a 6’11” wingspan, he converted 60% of his rim attempts and grabbed 10.8 rebounds per 40 minutes. His strength and aggressiveness make him a high-upside frontcourt scorer.

50.name: Matthias Hamilton
50.about: Hamilton stretches defenses with consistent shooting. At 6’7” with a 7’0” wingspan, he converted 37% of his threes while using craft and footwork to create space. His size and shooting touch make him a reliable scoring option from the wing.

51.name: Jonathan Ford
51.about: Ford attacks the rim with explosiveness and athleticism. At 6’5” with a 6’8” wingspan, he averaged 1.2 drives per 40 minutes in transition and isolation, finishing efficiently while creating opportunities for teammates.

52.name: Danny Schneider
52.about: Schneider uses size and length to finish in traffic and protect the rim. At 6’9” with a 7’0” wingspan, he averaged 1.01 points per possession on post-ups and 2.0 blocks per 40 minutes. Strength and finishing make him a reliable interior presence.

53.name: Brayan Hunt
53.about: Hunt stretches the floor with shooting and off-ball movement. At 6’3” with a 6’6” wingspan, he converted 38% of his threes while using craft and timing to create open looks, providing reliable spacing for his team.

54.name: Eric Welch
54.about: Welch excels as a scoring guard off the dribble and in catch-and-shoot situations. At 6’4” with a 6’8” wingspan, he hit 37% of his threes while using craft and footwork to create space and scoring opportunities.

55.name: Julian McGhee
55.about: McGhee attacks the rim with strength and craft, finishing efficiently in traffic. At 6’6” with a 6’9” wingspan, he averaged 1.0 points per close-range attempt while using physicality and footwork to create opportunities and contribute on both ends.

56.name: Bruno Correa
56.about: Correa uses strength and craft to score efficiently in the mid-paint. At 6’5” with a 6’7” wingspan, he converted 57% of his attempts inside while creating space for teammates. His combination of finishing ability and physicality makes him a reliable offensive weapon.

57.name: Abdoulaye Saint-Laurent
57.about: Saint-Laurent stretches the floor while protecting the rim. At 6’11” with a 7’3” wingspan, he converted 36% of his threes and averaged 2.1 blocks per 40 minutes. His length, defensive timing, and shooting touch give him versatility on both ends of the floor.

58.name: Makai Bridges
58.about: Bridges is a versatile guard who can score efficiently from mid-range and create for teammates. At 6’3” with a 6’9” wingspan, he converted 44% of his pull-up jumpers while averaging 1.2 assists per 40 minutes. His craft and size make him a reliable two-way option.

59.name: Rickey Britt
59.about: Britt creates offense with a mix of dribble penetration and perimeter shooting. At 6’1” with a 6’1” wingspan, he converted 39% of his three-pointers and averaged 1.0 assist per possession in pick-and-roll situations. His craft and shooting ability make him a reliable backcourt threat.

60.name: Joey Anderson
60.about: Anderson is a stretch big who can score in the post and knock down shots from distance. At 6’8” with a 6’9” wingspan, he converted 36% of his threes while averaging 9.8 rebounds per 40 minutes. His size and shooting touch give him versatility on both ends.
